>
> > Jake, Doc, list:
> > Doc Ric really had 2 questions here, compression ratio being the main
one.
> > What is really important is that the c/r not be set too high. Opinion
> varies and
> > expected gasoline quality would determine this (though recent drive
> reports from
> > Mexico indicate this is less of a problem than it used to be).
> > The maximum c/r would be somewhere in the 7.5/1 area and if you are
close,
> > better make sure you are accurate. Many would prefer a number more like
> 6.9-7.0.
> >
> > I  am of the belief that higher compression is free power, but of course
> it
> > comes at the slight cost of shorter engine life.
> > A few minutes spent with your machinist and you can either have him cc
> your
> > heads or explain how.
> > Second  was your statement about balancing. You really need to balance
the
> rods
> > end for end (IOW even out all the big end weights and all the small end
> weights
> > and then recheck the big ends). Many years ago I worked in a high
> performance
> > machine shop and balanced many rods. They use a special rig with rollers
> and a
> > counter balance, but I'm sure you could rig up something with knife
blades
> and a
> > gram (dealers') scale.
> > Balancing the reciprocating parts (pistons and rods)  only will give you
> the
> > best return on investment, if you are on a tight budget. I'd guess a
shop
> would
> > do it for about $50 or so.
> > Higher quality pistons like Mahles and NPR's were almost always perfect
> from the
> > factory.
> > Al Brase
> > 69 double cab, 80 westy
> >
> >

